{"id":"288120040_Coin_flipping_of_any_constant_bias_implies_one-way_functions","abstract":"We show that the existence of a coin-flipping protocol safe against any non-trivial constant bias (e.g., :499) implies the existence of one-way functions. This improves upon a re- cent result of Haitner and Omri [FOCS '11], who proved this implication for protocols with bias √ 2-1/2 - o(1) ≈ :207. Unlike the result of Haitner and Omri, our result also holds for weak coin-flipping protocols","authors":["Itay Berman","Iftach Haitner","Aris Tentes"],"meta":["May 2014Proceedings of the Annual ACM Symposium on Theory of Computing","DOI:10.1145/2591796.2591845"],"references":["277292952_Martingales_collective_coin_flipping_and_discrete_control_processes_Extended_Abstract","225198696_On_the_Black-Box_Complexity_of_Optimally-Fair_Coin_Tossing","221591794_A_Hard-Core_Predicate_for_all_One-Way_Functions","221355430_On_the_Cryptographic_Applications_of_Random_Functions","221354874_Protocols_for_Multiparty_Coin_Toss_With_Dishonest_Majority","220431496_How_to_construct_random_functions","3501880_One-way_functions_are_essential_for_complexity_based_cryptography","2641344_A_Pseudorandom_Generator_from_any_One-way_Function","2329734_Universal_One-Way_Hash_Functions_and_Their_Cryptographic_Applications","234786530_Limits_on_the_security_of_coin_flips_when_half_the_processors_are_faulty","221590317_One-Way_Functions_Are_Necessary_and_Sufficient_for_Secure_Signatures","221580812_Probabilistic_Quantifiers_Adversaries_and_Complexity_Classes_An_Overview","221499430_On_the_Computational_Complexity_of_Coin_Flipping","221498600_Coin_Flipping_with_Constant_Bias_Implies_One-Way_Functions","221355126_Coin_Flipping_by_Telephone","220618397_Statistically_Hiding_Commitments_and_Statistical_Zero-Knowledge_Arguments_from_Any_One-Way_Function","220479038_Bit_Commitment_Using_Pseudorandomness","220337103_An_Optimally_Fair_Coin_Toss","24268753_Optimal_Quantum_Strong_Coin_Flipping","1900535_Quantum_weak_coin_flip